{{Infobox stadium | name = Abbey Park | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Grimsby]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{Coord|53.5582|-0.0812|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1889 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = 1899 | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = 10,000 | dimensions = 114 x 75 yards | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] (1889–1899) }}
'''Abbey Park''' was a [[association football|football]] stadium in [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], England. It was the home ground of [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] between 1889 and 1899.
==History== Abbey Park was built as a replacement for Grimsby's previous ground, Clee Park. It consisted of a main seated stand on the northern touchline of the pitch and a raised bank on the southern touchline. Behind the eastern end of the pitch there was a 300-seat stand moved from Clee Park, alongside an 800-capacity terrace. The dressing rooms were located in the south-east corner of the ground.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p11, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref>
The ground was opened on 30 August 1889 with a friendly match against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Brom]], which Grimsby won 6–1. Grimsby became founder members of the [[Football League Second Division]] in 1892, and the first League game at Abbey Park on 3 September 1892 saw Grimsby beat [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] 2–1 in front of 5,000 spectators.<ref name=UD/>
The record attendance of 10,000 was set on 26 December 1896 for a match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] (with Grimsby winning 3–2) and equalled for an 8 April 1897 game against [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]], a game which Grimsby won 3–1. In 1899 Grimsby moved to [[Blundell Park]]; the final match at Abbey Park was played against [[Darwen F.C.|Darwen]] on 15 April 1899, with the 9–2 victory also being the ground's record home win.<ref name=UD/>
A housing development was later built on the site.<ref name=UD/>
